==English==
===Etymology===
Old English [[segnian|seġnian]], from Latin [[signare]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /seɪn/

===Verb===
{{en-verb|sain|sains|sained|saining}}
# ''(transitive, archaic)'' the make the [[sign]] of the [[cross]] on or over something or someone
# ''(intranitive, obsolete except in Scots)'' to make the [[sign]] of the [[cross]]
# ''(transitive, archaic)'' to [[bless]], to keep from evil influence
#:*'''1983''': The child was '''sained''' then.  Fir candles were lighted and whirled round the bed in which mother and infant lay. — Robert Nye, ''The Facts of Life''